  "prompt": "How are computers cooled and does it vary based on the size and function of the computer?",
  "response": "Computers are cooled using various methods, and the cooling solution can indeed vary based on the size, function, and performance requirements of the computer. Here are the main cooling methods:\n\n1. Air Cooling (Most Common)\n- Fans and heatsinks\n- Uses airflow to dissipate heat\n- Typical in desktop computers and laptops\n- Inexpensive and relatively efficient for moderate performance\n\n2. Liquid Cooling\n- Uses liquid (usually water or specialized coolant) to transfer heat\n- More efficient than air cooling\n- Often used in high-performance gaming PCs and workstations\n- Can be more expensive and complex\n\n3. Passive Cooling\n- No moving parts\n- Uses heat sinks and thermal design to dissipate heat\n- Common in small devices like smartphones and tablets\n- Limited cooling capacity\n\n4. Phase-Change Cooling\n- Uses refrigeration principles\n- Extremely effective but expensive\n- Primarily used in specialized high-performance computing\n\n5. Specialized Cooling for Large Systems\n- Data centers use:\n  - Advanced air conditioning\n  - Liquid cooling systems\n  - Immersion cooling (submerging hardware in dielectric fluid)\n\nThe cooling method depends on:\n- Computer size\n- Performance requirements\n- Power consumption\n- Cost\n- Environmental conditions\n\nEach method has specific advantages and is selected based on the computer's intended use.",
